english:
  title: Responding to a Rhyme at Floating Jade Pavilion
  author: Kwon Han-gong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I lead by hand the monks of Youngmyeong and Changgyeong,
    Poling a small boat through the middle of the Daedong River.
    As if arriving where the dust of the mortal world cannot reach,
    I strain to trace the very end of Changlang's waters.
    Of the wise men of old, who still remains to prove their worth?
    Drunk and drowsy, I rest while you too take your ease.
    South of Worlam, such places grow scarce beneath heaven—
    Chojeonseok grows old, and mist and rain weep their sorrow.
  footnotes:
    - 'Youngmyeong and Changgyeong temples: Buddhist temples on the Daedong River near Pyongyang.'
    - 'Changlang: A reference to the Miluo River in Chinese poetry, symbolizing purification and solitude; here applied to the Daedong River.'
    - 'Worlam (月岩): A famous scenic rock formation on the Daedong River.'
    - 'Chojeonseok (朝天石): Another celebrated rock on the river, literally ''Stone Facing Heaven.'''
